    {
        "content": "<p>Well, looking at both the answer, Urysohn’s theorem and Nagata-Smirnov’s theorem, I guess the characterization could be “a topological space is Lawvere metrizable iff it has a countably locally finite base”.</p>",
        "id": 476540533,
        "sender_full_name": "Jean-Baptiste Vienney",
        "timestamp": 1728754944
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/480731/83901\">I wrote an answer giving an exact characterization in the literature along with some discussion of related results</a>, although I think it's probably pretty unsatisfying. The exact characterization is morally pretty close to 'the topology is induced by a quasi-uniformity with a countable base.'</p>\n<p>Also, having a countably locally finite base is not a necessary condition for being Lawvere-metrizable (although it and a weaker condition is sufficient).</p>",
